==Reception==

===Critical reception===
{{unbalanced|section|date=September 2012}}
Although the show has had high viewership, it has received poor reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/critics-hate-us-but-they-never-say-how-the-audience-is-screaming-with-laughter-2589289.html|title=Critics hate us but they never say how the audience is screaming with laughter|first=Melanie|last=Finn|publisher=Herald.ie|date=22 March 2011|accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> From the start critics hated it; "The whole thing is entirely predicated on viewers finding a man dressed as a foul-mouthed elderly woman intrinsically funny", noted Bernice Harrison, TV reviewer with ''[[The Irish Times]]''. "If you do, you're away in a hack, and the viewing figures are astronomical, but if you don't, and you think that died out with [[Les Dawson]] and [[Dick Emery]], then it's a long half-hour."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2011/0212/1224289582149.html|title=It's not that 'Mrs Brown' is too mainstream. It's just not funny.|date=12 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2011|first=Bernice|last=Harrison|work=The Irish Times|publisher=Irish Times Trust}}</ref> The ''[[Irish Independent]]'' said that ''Mrs Brown's Boys'' was the type of TV programme "that makes you vaguely embarrassed to be Irish".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/why-irish-tv-has-the-cringe-factor-2547198.html|title=Why Irish TV has the cringe factor|date=19 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2011|work=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media}}</ref>

===Television ratings===

====Ireland====
''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' was a ratings success upon its initial broadcast in Ireland. Every episode aired won its timeslot for RT<U+00C9>, with an average viewership of 753,500 in January 2011. One episode's rating beat that of RT<U+00C9>'s own ratings giant ''[[The Late Late Show]]'', with 856,000 viewers tuning in to watch.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/mrs-browns-boys-put-it-up-to-tubridy-2526623.html|title=Mrs Brown's Boys put it up to Tubridy|date=5 February 2011|accessdate=5 February 2011|work=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media}}</ref> The 2011 Christmas episode was the most-watched TV show in Ireland over the holiday season, with a 48.6% audience share.<ref name=rte_christmas_2011_viewership>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/1228/ocarrollbrendan.html|title=Mrs Brown's Boys tops Christmas viewership|date=28 December 2011|accessdate=28 December 2011|work=RT<U+00C9> Ten|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann]]}}</ref> A year later the show again topped the Christmas ratings with "The Virgin Mammy" gaining an average of 972,000 viewers and a 47% share, and "Mammy Christmas" gaining an average of 851,000 viewers and a 51% share.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285676&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=RT<U+00C9> Television Tops Christmas 2012|publisher=The Irish Film & Television Network|first=Gear<U+00F3>id|last=Gilmore|date=2 January 2013|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref>

====United Kingdom====
Its opening in the UK won 16.4% of the ratings in its Monday night slot and was received well by viewers.<ref>Shah, Kavi. [http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/856281-mrs-browns-boys-rakes-in-2-6million-viewers-for-the-bbc "Mrs Brown's Boys rakes in 2.6million viewers for the BBC"], ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'', 22 February 2011.</ref> Despite the critical reviews, 2.9 million viewers had tuned in by the third episode.<ref>Lesnik, Tim. [http://www.inthenews.co.uk/news/entertainment/tv/mrs-brown-s-boys-to-make-bbc-one-return-$21386021.htm "Mrs Brown's Boys to make BBC One return"], 22 March 2011.</ref><ref>Scott, Marion. [http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/television-news/2011/03/20/brown-is-the-new-back-as-mrs-brown-s-boys-is-set-to-return-86908-23003641/ "Brown is the new back as Mrs Brown's Boys is set to return"], ''Daily Record'', 20 March 2011.</ref><ref>Sykes, Jaine. [http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/comedy/2011/03/mrs-browns-boys-returns-for-a.shtml "Mrs Brown will be back for a second series"], ''BBC Comedy Blog'' (BBC), 22 March 2011.</ref> The 2011 Christmas Special achieved 6.61 million viewers, winning in its 10&nbsp;pm time-slot.<ref name="digitalspy1">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a357402/david-jasons-the-royal-bodyguard-logs-71m-for-bbc-one.html |title=David Jason's 'The Royal Bodyguard' logs 7.1m for BBC One - TV News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=2011-12-27 |accessdate=2011-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0206/ocarrollb.html|title=Mrs Brown tops Ross in ratings|work=RT<U+00C9> Ten|publisher=RT<U+00C9>|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> Consolidated figures revealed the 2012 Christmas specials were the most watched programmes on Christmas Eve and Boxing Day respectively. "Mammy Christmas" gained 11.68m (41.3%) and "The Virgin Mammy" gained 10.72m (38.7%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/jan/04/mrs-browns-boys-festive-tv-ratings|title=Mrs Brown's Boys proves festive TV ratings hit|publisher=[[The Gaurdian]]|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref>
The first airing of the show usually averages around 10 million viewers with an additional 5 million viewing on the following Saturday repeat, adding up to almost 15 million views per episode.

===Awards===
In 2011 ''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' was nominated for a BAFTA award at the [[British Academy Television Awards 2011|British Academy Television Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/arts/ocarrolls-hit-comedy-nominated-for-bafta-award-2630215.html|title=O'Carroll's hit comedy nominated for BAFTA award|date=27 April 2011|accessdate=27 April 2011|first=Allison|last=Bray|work=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media}}</ref>  In February 2012, it won an [[Irish Film & Television Awards|IFTA]] for Best Entertainment Programme. At the [[2012 British Academy Television Awards|2012 BAFTA Television Awards]], ''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' won the award for Best Situation Comedy, and Brendan O'Carroll was nominated for the BAFTA for Best Male Performance in a Comedy Programme but lost to [[Darren Boyd]] for his role in the [[Sky1]] comedy series, ''[[Spy (2011 TV series)|Spy]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/what-eurovision-mrs-browns-boys-leads-the-irish-winners-at-the-bafta-awards-3120040.html|title=What Eurovision? Mrs Brown's Boys leads the Irish winners at the BAFTA awards|date= 27 May 2012|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=29 May 2012|first1=Mark|last1=Hilliard|first2=Ken|last2=Sweeney}}</ref> In September 2012, the show won best comedy at the [[TV Choice]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/mrs-browns-boys-wins-best-comedy-at-tvchoice-awards-in-london-3226739.html|title=<U+2018>Mrs Brown<U+2019>s boys<U+2019> wins best comedy at TVChoice awards in London|publisher=Independent.ie|date=11 September 2012|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref> In January 2013, ''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' won the [[National Television Awards|National Television Award]] for Best Situation Comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-01-23/national-television-awards-mrs-browns-boys-wins-best-sitcom|title=National Television Awards: Mrs Brown's Boys wins Best Sitcom|first=Paul|last=Jones|publisher=Radio Times|date=23 January 2013|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref>

==Distribution==

===DVD and Blu-ray releases===
More than one million copies of the first series of ''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' were sold on DVD in Ireland and the UK between October 2011 and February 2012. A complete series 1 and 2 box set was also released on 8 October 2012, containing the 2011 Christmas special as a content exclusive, therefore meaning if one wishes to own the special, they would have to buy the box set.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0213/mrsbrownsboys.html|title=Over 1m Mrs Brown's Boys DVDs sold|work=RT<U+00C9> Ten|publisher=RT<U+00C9>|date=13 February 2012|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>

Some of the episodes on the Series 1 DVD differ from their original broadcasts. Due to copyright issues, scenes where casts perform songs were edited out. These edits included a scene where Mrs Brown sings Happy Birthday, the entire cast singing [[The Proclaimers]] song, "[[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]" in episode 3, and a scene in episode 6 where Buster sings the theme tune to ''[[Mission Impossible]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}} No changes have been made to the Series 2 episodes on their DVD release.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}} A joke about being sued for singing a copyrighted song featured in the stage show ''Mrs Brown's Boys Live: Good Mourning Mrs Brown''.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}

On 11 October 2012, series 2 was released in Region 4<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ezydvd.com.au/search?q=mrs+browns+boys&t=all |title=mrs browns boys |publisher=Ezydvd.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-12-23}}</ref> in both standard form and a limited edition. The limited edition version contained the Christmas special. The Complete Collection was also released at the same time, containing all 13 episodes as well.

